    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-01-26T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-01-26T08:00:00-05:00" n="170"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d170">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15A5/18: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Great Britain</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Atherton</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-01-26T13:00:00+00:00"
                            >January 26, 1934—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received January 26—9:55 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>16. From Hugh Wilson. Your 16, January 24, 2 p.m. Craigie<note n="5"
                        xml:id="d170fn5">Robert L. Craigie, Counselor in the British Foreign
                        Office.</note> got in touch with me to inquire whether we had any views as
                    to naval conversations. I followed instructions in your cable and learned from
                    Craigie that the Admiralty also has not yet completed its studies. He had no
                    definite suggestions to make but again reverted to the possibility of his
                    proceeding to Washington en route to visit his wife’s family. Craigie was
                    especially desirous that conversations of a technical nature and very informal
                    and confidential in character should take place at the earliest possible moment
                    after the two Admiralties were ready.</p>
                <p>I did not encourage Craigie in thinking that his visit to Washington would be a
                    procedure which my Government would consider the most advantageous.</p>
                <p>Copy sent Geneva, [Wilson.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Atherton</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
